Creating images with R

with a little bit of magick

2023-03-12

My Meme

I used the existing meme format to express my first impression of R and my current impression of R after going through the first module of this course. Of course, I am looking forward to learning all the interesting and useful kinds of stuff I can do with R, not only to create memes! 

library(magick)

# square one
r_image <- image_read("http://media.ign.com/games/image/article/738/738102/gaijin4koma_peersblog_1200684654.jpg") %>%
  image_crop("500x350+0")

# square two
r_text <- image_blank(width = 500,
                      height = 350,
                      color = "#000000") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "R\nProgramming",
                 color = "#ffffff",
                 size = 80,
                 font ="impact",
                 gravity = "center")

# square three
meme_image <- image_read("https://i.kym-cdn.com/photos/images/newsfeed/000/131/896/gaijin4koma2_peersblog_1200684608.jpg?1307579749") %>%
  image_crop("500x350+0")

# square four
meme_text <- image_blank(width = 500,
                         height =350,
                         color = "#000000") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Meme\nCreation",
                 color = "#ffffff",
                 size = 80,
                 font ="impact",
                 gravity = "center")

# making each row
r_vector <- c(r_image, r_text)
top_row <- image_append(r_vector)
meme_vector <- c(meme_image, meme_text)
bottom_row <- image_append(meme_vector)

# putting it all together
meme <- c(top_row, bottom_row) %>%
  image_append(stack = TRUE) %>%
  image_scale(800)

# save image
image_write(meme, "my_meme.png")

My animated GIF

I couldnt think of an original meme to make into an animated GIF, so I just decided to show images of the four seasons. 

# creating each image frame with text
image1 <- image_read("https://media.istockphoto.com/id/1362953676/photo/cherry-blossoms-close-up.jpg?b=1&s=170667a&w=0&k=20&c=CitSxlPy5AYu0IhhgQcxem5AETt_Fyu22ppWiRWnGJ4=") %>%
  image_scale(500)
frame1 <- image_blur(image1, 10,2) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "SPRING",
                   color = "#000000",
                   size = 80,
                   font ="Palatino",
                   gravity = "center")

image2 <- image_read("https://media.istockphoto.com/id/520298522/photo/working-online-from-a-tropical-beach-with-laptop-computer.jpg?s=612x612&w=0&k=20&c=QPuW0gg-oK3b_T4aB_FvoYVUgRhVFSQxPtLHeGWHns4=") %>%
  image_scale(500)
frame2 <- image_blur(image2, 10,2) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "SUMMER",
                 color = "#000000",
                 size = 80,
                 font ="Palatino",
                 gravity = "center")

image3 <- image_read("https://images.pexels.com/photos/33109/fall-autumn-red-season.jpg?cs=srgb&dl=pexels-pixabay-33109.jpg&fm=jpg") %>%
  image_scale(500)
frame3 <- image_blur(image3, 10,2) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "FALL",
                 color = "#000000",
                 size = 80,
                 font ="Palatino",
                 gravity = "center")

image4 <- image_read("https://images.pexels.com/photos/235621/pexels-photo-235621.jpeg?cs=srgb&dl=pexels-pixabay-235621.jpg&fm=jpg") %>%
  image_scale(500)
frame4 <- image_blur(image4, 10,2) %>%
  image_annotate(text = "WINTER",
                 color = "#000000",
                 size = 80,
                 font ="Palatino",
                 gravity = "center")

# putting the frame together
frames <- c(frame1, frame2, frame3, frame4)
# creating and saving the animated gif
image_animate(frames, fps = 1) %>% image_write("my_animation.gif")
